title: For Sale:  New .223/5.56 Wylde Chambered 7.5” AR Pistol Upper, KeyMod
postcontent: This is a new, never fired, AR Pistol upper in .223/5.56 assembled from USA produced parts (except where noted). Head space verified. The Wylde chambering allows safe and accurate use of both .223 and 5.56 ammo. Attaches directly to any Mil-Spec AR Pistol Lower. Inexpensive quality build. No BCG or Charging Handle. Shipping to be paid by Buyer. More images available. • 7.5” 1in7 Stainless Steel Barrel, Wylde • 7.0”Free-Float Aluminum KeyMod Hand Guard • Anderson Mil-Spec 7075T6 Upper, M4 Feed Ramps • Low Profile AISI Steel Phosphated Gas Block • Stainless Steel Anderson Pistol Length Gas Tube • Levang linear muzzle device • Ejection Port Door, USA • Forward Assist, Israeli Military Industries (IMI) NOTE: The following is based on my opinions. I’m not a lawyer and I don’t pretend to offer legal advice. Do your own research. There is nothing magical or quasi-anything about AR Pistols. The above discussed AR Upper is just that, an AR Upper. It’s not a ‘pistol’ or a ‘rifle’ in this configuration. I refer to it as a pistol because I’m thinking ‘pistol’ and if anyone wants to think ‘rifle’ (as in SBR, Short Barrel Rifle) then that’s their concern. An AR Lower can be a “Pistol Lower” or a “Rifle Lower”. This is merely a designation based upon a collection of parts and the intended use of the lower, also called “Constructive Intent”. This is a hugely important point. An AR lower created as a “Rifle Lower” must remain a rifle lower and the fitment of a barrel less than 16” is a modification to the rifle creating an Undocumented SBR. Having said that, it is quite easy to stay on the sunny side of life and the BATF and complete your AR Pistol without concern. As I am aware, an AR lower that is initially assembled as a “Pistol Lower”, can be used as a pistol lower and also can be converted to a rifle lower and back again as often as you wish. A Pistol Lower will have a buffer tube (receiver extension), maybe with a pad, and/or one of a couple of approved products like the SIG Brace or the KAK Industry Shockwave. To use the same” Pistol Lower” as an AR Rifle and fired from the shoulder, you will likely have some sort of buttstock. This is another hugely important point. If the buttstock ends up on your pistol upper, you have made it into an SBR. The best way to create yourself an AR Pistol is to buy a stripped AR lower and build it into a “Pistol Lower”. This is not at all a difficult process. An important point; make all your new stripped lowers into pistol lowers first. Also, you cannot use a Vertical Grip on an AR Pistol unless its overall length is 26” or greater. A vertical grip on an AR Pistol shorter than 26” creates an undocumented AOW (Any Other Weapon). The AFG (Angled Foregrip) or similar is legal for the AR Pistol.

title: For Sale:  Remington Model 600 6mm, BEAUTIFUL
postcontent:
Father in law has decided to sell off some of his collection, some very interesting rifles will be coming up for sale.

Listed here is a Remington Model 600, chambered in 6mm, with an 18" barrel.

The rifle is equipped with a Leupold Vari-X II 2-7 scope, with Weaver mounts. 
I am not entirely sure of the history of this rifle and I'm unsure if this is the original stock or not, educate me if you are more aware than I! But, it is a beautiful stock and if not original it has to be a higher end custom job.
Also, unsure of the trigger but it is the smoothest and lightest trigger I've ever pulled. Just bought a brand new Model 700 SPS Tactical and this trigger makes the 700 SPS feel like dragging a 2x4 over sandpaper.

Overall, the rifle is in great shape. This a fairly rare model, as the 600 was only produced between 1964 and 1967. The stock is near perfect condition, the bluing of the barrel shows very minor "wear", as pictured.

The rifle will also come with 69 rounds of factory ammunition in the original boxes. One could estimate the box's are from the 60's as well. 27 brass cases also included. Lastly, a brown rifle case is included, likely to have been purchased with the rifle originally. 

From what I can tell, an original 600 with a "standard" stock and nothing else included goes for around $600-800.
I'm going to start off with asking $800 for everything.

Please let me know any questions you may have!

Max

Hornady 366 Reloader 20ga 2.75"
Hornady's 366 Auto Shotshell Reloading Press is the ideal press for the avid target shooter. The time-tested design lets you load high-quality, low-cost ammo in a hurry, just set the case and wad in place, and pull the handle. The 366 Auto does the rest, automatically.
FEATURES INCLUDE:
PRIMER TUBE FILLER
Every 366 Auto includes our Primer Tube Filler. Holds a full box of shotshell primers, and fills the tube with a turn of the dial. Will not drop primers upside-down into the tube.
EASY EMPTY POWDER AND SHOT HOPPER TUBES
If you need to empty your powder or shot, this entire assembly can be easily removed without spilling, a feature unique to the 366 Auto. Baffles let powder and shot flow more smoothly for more uniform loads from start to finish.
AUTOMATIC PRIMER FEED SYSTEM
Makes priming shells automatic with the pull of the handle. Extremely smooth and reliable design reduces to nearly zero the chances of crushing the primer. Primer Tube Filler ensures no upside-down primers enter the feeder tube.
THREE-STAGE TAPER LOC CRIMPING
Starts crimp, closes and tapers. Perform more reliable crimping with both six or eight point crimps. Give factory taper to your shells.
PRIMER FEEDER SHUT-OFF (optional)
SPRING LOADED SEATER PUNCH (optional)
STANDARD SHOT AND POWDER BUSHINGS
These easy-to-change standard bushings make it easy to switch to a different shot or powder for most popular target loads.
POWDER SHUT-OFF AND SHOT SHUT-OFF
The shut-offs for powder and shot let you operate the machine as you need to by shutting off individual stations.
SWING-OUT WAD GUIDE
The wad guide swings out to give you better access, making it easier to place the wad. Helps to speed up your reloading.
AUTOMATIC INDEXING
Each pull of the lever automatically rotates the shell plate, so you do not have to do it manually. You will be amazed at how much faster and smoother your reloading efforts go with auto indexing.
FULL-LENGTH RESIZING STATION
You can resize your shells to factory dimensions, or skip this station entirely and speed up your reloading. Many presses force you to resize. The 366 Auto gives you the choice.
PRIMER CATCHER
Every pull of the handle ejects the spent primer from fired shells into the primer catcher for neat, easy disposal.
AUTOMATIC SHELL EJECTION
Completed shells are automatically ejected behind the press, so you don't have to remove them manually. Another speed advantage over other presses.
SHOT DRAIN HOLES IN SHELL PLATE

title: For Sale:  Russian SKS with 1200 rounds steel core ammo
postcontent: First, yes, an FFL is required to transfer. This is a Russian type 45 SKS. The SKS is one of the best rifles and the Russian is the best of the SKSs. These are very well made and have a chrome lined bore. They last forever. I used it as my hog gun in northern California so it has some scuffs and dings from much carrying but only approximately 150 rounds fired through it. The receiver is drilled and tapped for a scope mount but I no longer have the mount as I found the scope to be a hindrance in the thick brush encountered in hog hunting. When I did have the scope it would group 5 rounds into about 2.5 inches at 100 yards easily. This is really good for a semi automatic military type rifle. Also included is between 1150 and 1200 rounds of East German steel core armor piercing ammo and 400 rounds of regular ammo. Also included is (39) 10 round stripper clips. The East German ammo is very accurate and I have never had a malfunction of any kind with it. Actually I have never had a malfunction of any kind with this rifle but from past experience I believe real military ammo to be more reliable than commercial ammo. The regular ammo is just for the fun shooting. I would consider a partial trade for a lever action .357 or a Glock or Sig 9mm. I don't hunt anymore so except for a fun rifle such as the 357 lever I can't see what else I might be interested in although you could run something by me. We might also consider a small camping trailer but nothing too big or heavy.
